column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at an in transit storage facility pending final delivery.  During a routine inspection, it was discovered that a small amount of material had leaked from a packaged onto the floor of the van trailer and the parking area where the vehicle was staged.  Facility personnel immediately initiated a response and after donning the appropriate personnel protective equipment, entered the trailer, identified the leaking package and placed it into a suitable salvage drum.  IN addition, all clean-up debris was collected and placed into the salvage drum.  Once complete, the shipment was received by the intended facility and properly disposed of.  It is believed that the cause of the release can be attributed to a pinhole leak that developed on the bottom of the container.
column169: At the time the containers were accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed.  The driver was advised of the incident and was re-instructed to insure that before accepting any container for transportation he must insure that any external corrosion or rust be further inspected to insure the structural integrity of the container will withstand the rigors of transportation.  If any container is of suspect condition, proper steps must be initiated to either place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before transportation.  The driver has also been advised that future incidents can lead to disciplinary action up to and including termination.

column168: While being switched at the KCS Baton Rouge, Louisiana rail road yard, tank car PPG 1593 was discovered leaking from a slightly open liquid line (B-End). KCS immediately isolated the area and made proper notifications per local, state and federal requirements. KCS mobilized local railroad safety qualified emergency response service provider United States Environmental Services of Baton Rouge, LA.  The responder found the B-end liquid line secondary closure plug completely out (unapplied to the valve opening) and the liquid line valve (B-end) slightly open allowing the PIH hazmat release. The valve was properly closed and the plug was applied with teflon tape tool tight. All other closures were inspected and checked for proper securement.

column168: A vacuum tanker containing approximately 800 gallons of a nitric acid solution was en route to the intended waste disposal facility when the driver discovered a leak coming from a pipe between the tank and the discharge valve.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, he utilized his spill kit and the absorbent pads to contain the leak.  He attempted to slow the leak by putting vacuum on the trailer until the response crew arrived.  The response crew set up trenches to stop any groundwater contamination and began transferring the material into portable totes.  The Ohio EPA was notified and assigned case number 1004-18-829 to the incident.  The local fire department sent a representative out by car to observe the cleanup along with the Ohio EPA.  They were both satisfied with the cleanup efforts and left.  A 20 cubic yard roll off container was sent to remove the contaminated soil.  Once emptied, the cargo tank was placed out of service and sent to a maintenance facility for repairs and re-inspection.  The totes containing the remainder of the material (757 gallons) and the contaminated soil were taken to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: At the time the cargo tank was loaded, the driver identified no issues and/or deficiencies with the cargo tank during his pre-trip inspection.  The driver's actins taken during the trip succeeded in identifying the issue and his initial response activities controlled the spill and prevented a more serious release.  All drivers will continue to conduct their required inspections and will take those actions necessary to minimize the effects of any release that occurs during transportation.    The maintenance department is investigating the defective pipe to see what caused the release.  Up until this incident, there had been no previous problems with this component.

column168: Davenport bobtail unit # B-06 is currently at Tampa Freightliner for repairs. Last night at approximately 8:00 pm I received a call from Frank McCrary with Airgas South indicating we had a release on our truck at Freightliner in Tampa. Frank and I tried to determine where the leak was coming from to see if it could be resolved while he was on site but were unsuccessful. At this time I was still at the Davenport facility in the process of loading an Aqua tanker and couldn’t immediately break free. I called our driver Mark Calvelage who is the primary driver of B-06 to get assistance. Mark called Frank and was able to determine that one of the bypass valves had been closed causing the Hydrostat on the hose reel side of the bypass to release. Mark asked Frank to slightly open the bypass valve to relieve the pressure back into the tank but were unsuccessful at getting the Hydro to reseat. I left the Davenport facility at approximately 9:00pm and called Butch Johnson to advise of the situation. I arrived on site at approximately 10:00pm. Frank and Jim Sumner, also with Airgas South, were on scene. At this time all pressure had been relieved and there was no indication of a leak. Both Frank and Jim immediately insisted that the truck be removed from the Freightliner facility. After evaluating I also determined that it was the Hydro. I told them that I could replace the Hydro and isolate the valve and that would take care of the problem but they repeatedly insisted that Freightliner wanted the truck off the property. I assured them that I would take care of getting it transported back to Davenport at which time Frank and Jim both left the Freightliner facility. I replaced the Hydro and isolated all the vales. I placed valve caps and locks on all the valves and checked for leaks with Litmus Paper and found none. I spoke to Chris Bodmer (night manager @ Freightliner) and he said as long as there were no leaks he was okay with us leaving the truck there. Chris and I went over the truck to verify any signs of leaks and he was comfortable with leaving it onsite and gave me written permission. I left Freightliner at approximately 12:15 am. I was back at Freightliner this morning at 6:40 am to verify the condition and all is fine. This morning I spoke to Vern Gelser in the service department and explained what transpired last night to make sure he was okay with leaving it and he was fine.       Tony Clay  Facility Manager  Airgas Specialty Products  3600 CR 547 N  Davenport, Fl. 33837

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a Clean Harbors' in-transit storage facility for the purpose of consolidting less than truckload quantities for continued transportation.  During the transfer operation, it was discovered that approximately one gallon of residual liquid escaped from a flexible intermediate bulk package onto the floor of the van trailer.  Facility personnel placed the container into a containment area and repackaged the contents into suitable UN1A2 non-bulk  packages.  All material used to clean up the release will be containerized within UN1A2 containers and will be sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, the driver detected no evidence of liquid or of a release.  It is believed that during the course of transportation, residual liquids that were not visible at the time of the pick-up seperated from the solid matter during the rigors of transportation.  This residual escaped from the packaged during transit.    In order to prevent a recurrance, the driver has been instructed to continue to inspect each container before it is accepted for transportation and to take appropriate action if issues are discovered.  In addition, the shipper has been advised of the issue and has been requested to take those steps necessary to insure any residual liquid is removed from the material prior to shipping of.  If this is not possible, to select an alternate container that is suitable for liquid/solid mixtures.

column168: A box was received with no hazardous materials shipping labels on the outside of the package.  Upon opening the box, the packing slip indicated that the material was hydrochloric acid, 32%.  Inside of the box was a tied-off plastic bag.  Upon opening the bag, the smell of hydrochloric acid was present.  Further investigation revealed 4, 1-quart bottles of hydrochloric acid solution were wrapped in absorbent material and placed inside the bag.  The lids did not seem secure and there was some ineffective packaging tape over the lids.  The labels on the bottles looked like they had been exposed to hydrochloric acid.  However, no liquid was present in the bag and the absorbent material had not visible signs of a spill.  Additionally, there was no material safety data sheet provided with the shipment.
column169: The box should have included hazardous material shipping labels.  The hydrochloric acid should be packaged in better sealed containers.

column168: On 04/06/10 at 07:19 hours, personnel in the CSXT Southover yard in Savannah, GA discovered GATX 57066, a loaded tank car of Flammable Liquids N.O.S., emitting an odor from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Temple Inland was notified via CHEMTREC #2010-04-06-00040.  Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found eight of eight manway securement bolts/nuts less than tool tight.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to Temple Inland's representative, Moira Layman (409-746-7415). Contractor personnel properly tightened the manway securement bolts/nuts with a wrench and the leak stopped.  The tank car was decontaminated and released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code:  200  NARRI: 5 (5+5+0) X (2+0) = 100

column168: While being switched at the KCS Beaumont, Texas railroad classification yard crew detected lading release from the fill hole on top of tank carACFX 94714, load Sulfuric Acid, Spent, Class 8, UN1832.  The lading spillage occurred when tank car was moved.  The tank car was isolated to prevent further movement in track #4 where found. Emergency services were mobilized.  Responders found that 2 of the 3 fill hole cover bolts were not applied. The three fill hole cover bolts were applied tool tight mitigating the release.  The released materials was neutralized and cleaned up.     KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 will apply. KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 will apply.    Note to report, item 27, amount in package, was estimated because bulk quantities are provided on shipping paper as "1 Tank Car" per DOT requirements.  Carrier is not provided specific quantity. This action required by preparer to facilitate data acceptance by DOT IT system edits.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.

column168: Shipment arrived at Korean Air cargo facility Building #9 J.F.K. International Airport under an inbound transfer from DHL Building #263. The shipment was located inside of a DHL ULD AAX3246DHL with two of the total three pieces doubled stacked in the container. The stacked skids were removed together from the containers due they were slightly leaning to one side. Upon separating the skidsthe forklift operator accidentally punctured one of the bags on the bottom skid. The area was  immediately cordon off and the Port Authority Police were notified.
column169: The main cause of this incident was the double stacking of the dangerous goods skids while being transferred from one facility to another. We have requested DHL  that in the future not to transfer cargo in this manner. We have also requested that  our ground handling agent Cargo Airport Services provided additional training to their forklift operators. Stressing that individual staff should seek assistance from others while attemping difficult tasks. This incident could have been avoided  if other staff were there to stabilize and level the top skid so that the forklift  blades could have enter the wooden skid cleanly and not puncture the content.

column168: On 04/05/10 at 18:18 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Tilford yard in Atlanta, GA, discovered tank car NTLX 1010, a load of Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S. leaking from the protective housing area. The car was isolated and the shipper, Shell Trading Company, was notified via CHEMTREC #2010-04-05-00179.  Chris Machenberg, CSXT hazardous materials manager, was dispatched to the scene along with Eagle SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor and found the liquid line valve to be defective. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper contact, Rick Ferguson, 281-380-2019 who dispatched RESCAR to remove the defective valve and place a blind flange on the liquid valve fitting temporarily while the railcar is held awaiting a new replacement valve. The valve will be replaced and qualified prior to departing Tilford yard. This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 300  NARRI: 2 (5+1+0) X (2+0) = 24

column168: GATX 79816 was noted by carrier personnel with product leaking from the top of the car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, WEL Environmental, responded and found liquid material leaking from both reclosing pressure relief devices.  Attempts to relieve the pressure on the car through the vapor line valve and the manway resulted in liquid product being released indicating the car was overfilled and had no vapor space.    After allowing the car to cool overnight the manway cover was opened and the car was noted as shell full.    Approximately 1,075 gallons of material was removed from the car and all fittings resecured stopping the release.

column168: On 04/11/10 at 00:51 hours, personnel in the CSXT Hamlet yard in Hamlet, NC discovered UTLX 662069, a loaded tank car of Flammable Liquid, N.O.S. leaking from the manway area. The car was isolated and the shipper, Bowater Incorporated, was notified via Chemtrec #2010-04-11-00003. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the tank car was missing the 20" teflon manway cover gasket. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper representative, Calvin Catoe, 803-981-8659. Hepaco personnel replaced the gasket the following day and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transportation to final destination. This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 207  NARRI:  5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60

column168: While at the UPRR Livonia, LA rail yard, tank car was found to have a slight vapor release from beneath the man way cover plate. One of six man way swing bolts was less than tool tight. This bolt could not be properly secured as the washer was missing. Further inspection revealed that the man way cover plate gasket was worn and defective. Additionally, the air valve plug, the liquid valve plug and the sample valve plug were less than tool tight. The gasket was replaced with a onetime use, gor-tek gasket that secured the car from leaking. In addition, the three loose plugs were secured properly. Shipping papers indicated that the car was moving on FRA movement approval FRA 10040199, for stripped man way bolt.

column168: CN transportation department employee reported a "hissing" noise coming from the top of tank car PROX 91669 (L/ Carbon Dioxide, Refrigerated Liquid) during switching operations at the CN Kirk Yard, Gary, IN. The employee proceeded upwind and reported feeling "light headed", sitting down between tracks. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated in track. Fire Department notified, transporting the employee to a local hospital where he was treated and released to full duty.  CN's response team responded noting the tank car was venting as part of it's normal operation. No excess flow, vapors or icing noted. Area monitored, oxygen readings on and near the car were within normal range. Employee interview noted he was never down wind of the tank car. On 04/14/2010, shipper's technician inspected the car noting no exceptions, tank car released for movement.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: An intermodal container was picked up from the Port of Houston for transport to the intended waste disposal facility.  The driver had checked the container prior to pickup and there was no sign of leakage.  When offloading the container at the 10 day storage yard at the intended waste disposal facility, the rear of the cover leaked material over the rear door onto the concrete containment area.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, a response crew shoveled the material back into the container and cleaned up the affected area.
column169: The container was loaded to capacity and when the container was offloaded, the angle forced some of the sludge material between the cover and the rear door.  The origin location was notified to not load the boxes up to the top, and the desitnation will use better care when offloading.

column168: An intermodal container containing hazardous waste was picked up at the Port of Houston to go to the intended waste disposal facility. column168: Load bar holding up freight in front of shipment failed, cause heavy freight in front to fall backwards on top of this single box. Found it with the bottom 2 inch's of the box wet. No liquid was on the floor or other freight. The lid seemed to pop open and spill a small amount when hit. Once discovered the box was immediately placed in a recovery container to prevent any further spillage.
column169: Single small boxes of Hazmat should not be on a skid, they should be loose so that it can be placed out of the way of possible falling freight. When on a skid it has to take the area of a skid space so that if something falls the single box takes the full force. This can be minimized if the box was loose by surrounding the loose box by other freight to soften impact if something was to fall. Also plywood could be used on top of several boxes to distribute the force over all objects if the falling freight hits in a small area, like with the corner of the pallet hitting first.

column168: CN transportation department employee noted product coming from the top of tank car CTCX 732409(L / ALCOHOLS, N.O.S.) during switching operations at the CN Markham Yard, East Hazel Crest, IL. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting shipper's seal intact, sample valve fully open and sample valve plug less than tool tight allowing product to escape. Valve closed, plug secured, new seal applied and tank car released for movement.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: At approximately 2300 hrs on 4/7/10 a PTRA train crew noticed product leaking from tank car JRSX 1006, a phosphoric acid load, whenever the car was moved during normal flat switching activities in track 204 at American Yard.  DTS Jack Forsyth was notified and responded to the scene. He noted that there was some residue on the side of the tank near the manway but it was not an active leak. At that time it was determined that the car could be moved with care to track 210 where it could be isolated overnight and repaired by emergency response crews. Forsyth assisted the crew in slowly moving the car to track 210 to prevent further leakage. M&M Protection was called to the scene and made the necessary repairs to the tank car at approximately 900 AM on 4/8/10. It has been estimated that less than one gallon of product leaked from the tank car down the sides of the tank shell. A very small amount of product was noted on the ballast. M&M neutralized the product on the ground and cleaned the sides of the tank.
column169: The shipper J R Simplot was notified of the issues with JRSX 1006. They are investigating the incident and takin steps to prevent similar problems in the future.

column168: On April 5th, 2010, at approximately 1800 hours, a Pinnacle Express truck #118, pulling trailer #158 was attempting to deliver 6000 gallons of aviation gasoline to the Madison Municipal Airport in Madison, Indiana. As the truck made the turn from W. Interstate Block Rd (Westbound) to (Northbound) Borcherding Rd, the driver cut the corner too short and the right side trailer tires left the roadway and dropped into a drainage culvert. This resulted in the tractor trailer rolling over onto it's right side.     Madison Township Fire Department was dispatched to the scene. FD personnel placed absorbant pads under a leaking manway to absorb a small leak that was present at the manway. EQ Environmental staff was dispatched to the scene as well as Indiana Department of Environmental Management (IDEM) representatives.     Holes were drilled into the left (top) side of the tanker and the product was pumped off into another tanker. The overturned tractor trailer was righted after the product was removed and towed to repair facilities. Per EQ's report, an estimated 2 to 10 gallons of product was released into containment equipment over the duration of the incident.    Summit Environmental returned to the site on April 9th, 2010 to perform remediation acitivites that included removing some soil for testing, and restoring the culvert to it's original condition.     No injuries or fatalities resulted from this incident. Three households were evacuated per the Madison Twp FD for approximately 12 hours while transfer efforts were underway.
column169: Pinnacle Express will no longer deliver fuel to this airport utilizing the route that was taken on April 5th, 2010. Airport direction signs have been requested to be moved to a safer route for delivery vehicles.

column4: A specification cargo tank 1,000 gallons or greater containing any hazardous materials that (1) received structural damage to the lading retention system or damage that requires repair to a system int
column168: Vehicle traveling in right hand lane of 4 lane divided highway. While negotiating a slight right curve, driver dropped coffee cup and leaned over to pick it up. Vehicle left roadway into center grass median, striking metal guard rail with left rear of cargo tank and continued against guard rail for 15 feet until striking concrete bridge abuttment and coming to rest. Impact caused rear axle of trailer to rotate under frame of carge tank, crushing delivery piping at rear of trailer. Ther was no release of cargo. The vehicle could not be driven from scene. Another cargo tanker was dispatched to the scene and successfully transfered the cargo from the damaged cargo tanker. The cargo tank was removed from the scene by wreckers on a flatbed trailer. The entire operation lasted approximately 12 hours and was supervised by the Florida Department of Transportation. The accident caused the closure of 1 eastbound lane for 1 1/2 hours during the cargo transfer.
column169: Given the severity of the impact damage, the packaging performed flawlessly. The cargo was loaded through the top of the cargo tank which meant that the discharge piping that failed contained no material. This incident was the direct result of distracted driving and we chose to terminate the drivers' employment.

On 04/07/10 at 09:26 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Avon yard in Avon, IN discovered UTLX 642931, a residue tank car of Coal Tar Distillates, Flammable, leaking from the manway area of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Marathon Petroleum, representative Roger Spring (877-627-5463), was contacted. Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene to make repairs.  Upon arrival, Summit personnel found the manway cover to be misaligned, the gasket was cracked in several places and 3 of 8 manway bolts were less than tool tight. The shipper contacted Bobby Breed of Specialized Response Systems (SRS) to assist with Summits response. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper via Bobby Breed of SRS (817-246-3338). Contractor personnel replaced the gasket, tightened the manway bolts and the leak stopped. The car was decontaminated and released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 209  NARRI: 5(4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70

column168: Quality Carriers claim number 27751 involved a leaking cargo tanker.  The tanker was carrying UN2924, Flammable liquids, corrosive, nos (Isopropanol, Methyl Trialkyl Ammonium Chloride), 3, (8), II.  Approximately 1 gallon of product was released onto the top and side of the tanker.  The released product did not impact any water, soil, or any other surface.  The cause of the release was an open valve near the dome lid of the tanker.  An environmental contractor, Freeman's, was dispatched to perform cleanup.  After the tanker was cleaned, and the valve was properly closed, the tanker left the site.
Tank was sealed and the clock gauge was inoperative- giving a false reading. The tank was overfilled by 401 gallons

column168: A BNSF mechanical rail car inspector (carman) inspecting an inbound train consist in the railyard reported entrained UTLX 11147 (DOT 111A100W2 tank car) with fresh product stains on its sideshell. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders were notified and inspected UTLX 11147. Responders reported no shipper seals were present or affixed onto the top fittings. The liquid valve was found partially open with its closure plug not tool tight. The responders closed the liquid valve and tool tightened the closure plug. Spillage on the sideshell was neutralized with baking soda/water solution. Afterwards, observed ground impact spillage was also neutralized with a baking soda/water solution. Response was concluded by 1230 hrs. CDT, 4/03/2010.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: AT APPROX 5:10 PM ON APRIL 12, 2010 OUR EMPLOYEE DRIVING ONE OF OUR PETROLEUM DELIVERY TRUCKS WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON A COUNTRY ROAD 1300 IN SHELBY COUNTY, ILLINOIS.  OUR DRIVER CAME UP ON A VEHICLE COMING HIS WAY DOWN THIS NARROW COUNTRY ROAD AND THE OTHER VEHICLE WAS IN THE CENTER OF THE ROAD.  OUR DRIVER AVOIDED HITTING THE OTHER VEHICLE BUT IN DOING SO GOT OFF THE SIDE OF THE ROAD WHERE THE ROAD WAS EXTRA NARROW WITH A DEEP DITCH ALONG SIDE THE ROAD.  OUR VEHICLE GOT PULLED INTO THE DITCH AND IT OVERTURNED.  EVEN THOUGH OUR PETROLEUM DELIVERY TRUCK HAD BULK GAS AND DIESEL ON HIS TRUCK IN SEPARATE COMPARTMENTS, THE TANK WALLS AND PLUMBING KEPT IT'S INTEGRITY AND DID NOT RUPTURE OR BREAK.  WHILE THE TRUCK WAS ON ITS SIDE IN THE DITCH THE GASOLINE IN ONE OF THE CARGO COMPARTMENT TANKS WAS UP AGAINST THE TOP HATCH OF THE TANK.  THE HATCH OR LID HELD THE PRODUCT FROM LEAKING OUT BUT THE HATCH OR LID IS CONFIGURED WITH A VENT FOR EXPANSION AND CONTRACTION AND THAT VENT WAS LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE GASOLINE OUT ON TO THE GROUND INTO THE ROAD DITCH.  WE RESPONDED AS SOON AS WE COULD TO THE ACCIDENT BY TAKING SOME ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO THE SITE TO CATCH THE DRIP FROM THE VENT ON THE HATCH.  WE ALSO PUT DOWN ABSORBENT MATERIAL ON THE PRODUCT SPILLED OUT ON TO THE GROUND AND THEN MADE TWO BERMS OR DAMS IN THE ROAD DITCH TO KEEP THE SPILLED PRODUCT FROM LEAVING THE SITE.  WE GOT A WRECKER OUT TO THE SITE AND LIFTED THE TANK UP AND OUT OF THE DITCH AND THEN WITH AN AUXILIARY TANK AND PUMP WE PULLED THE REMAINING PRODUCT OFF OF THE WRECKED TANK TRUCK INTO ANOTHER TANK TRUCK FOR SAFE KEEPING.  WE ALSO HAD BODINE ENVIRONMENTAL RESPOND TO THE ACCIDENT SITE WITHIN A COUPLE HOURS TO SUPERVISE IN CONTAINING THE SPILLAGE AND PUT DOWN FRESH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PULL UP THE SATURATED ABSORBENT AND AFTER APPROVAL FROM THE RESPONDING EPA REPRESENTATIVE THE SITE WAS AGAIN SERVICE AGAIN THE NEXT MORNING BY BODINES TO PULL UP THE SATURATED ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PUT DOWN NEW.  THE ON FRIDAY THE 16TH, 2010 BODINES CAME BACK OUT AND HAD A BACK HOE DIG UP THE CONTAMINATED AREA AND PUT IT ON SITE ON PLASTIC AND TOOK SAMPLES SO THAT THE CONTAMINATION COULD ENTER AN APPROVED LANDFILL.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column25: Noble Americas Corp. by Husker AG, LLC
column168: A BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard revealed entrained UTLX 41132 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was leaking product from its top fitting area. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected UTLX 41132. The responders reported that the closed liquid valve was one full turn loose on its threaded connection and product was escaping from this valve's mounting base connection. After the liquid valve was tool tightened, no further product release was evident. All spillage on UTLX 41132 evaporated and no ground impact was observed. Response was concluded by 1750 hrs. PDT, 4/25/2010.

column168: A hazardous waste shipment was being loaded from the ten day temporary intransit storage facility onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility.  When the drum was moved, a small "ring puddle" was noticed on the floor.  The dockworker, who was wearing the proper personal protective equipment, turned the drum over and noticed a small pinhole leak around the seam.  A suitable salvage container was used to overpack the drum and the absorbent pad used to clean up the floor.  The drum was then loaded into the trailer for the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: At the time of pickup and also when the drum was unloaded off the truck used to pick it up, there was no sign of any leakage.  The small leak from the seam developed while the drum was sitting at the intransit storage facility.  No leak was noticed during routine inspections as the liquid was contained under the drum.  The generator was notified as to the use of used drums for this material.

column168: Drivers were loading shipments that were staged on the dock when one driver noticed that one of the pallets was damaged and had leaked some of the product. He then brought it to the attention of a supervisor. The supervisor inspected the pallet and found that one carton on the bottom of the pallet had been struck by an unknown object. The bottom carton was removed from the pallet and opened. One jug was found to be crushed and the bottom and was slightly dripping. The jug was put in a 5 gallon recovery pail upside down to prevent further leaks. The driver that discovered the pallet and the other driver on the dock were questioned as to their knowledge of the damage and neither knew how the damage occurred. Very little of the product had leaked and even as the jug was lifted out of the carton the jug did not leak, presumably due to the fact that puncture was small and at the bottom of the jug which was air tight.
column169: Raise awareness of incident that occurred with all drivers and the need to be aware while operating on the dock. Place shipments susceptible to damages in areas less likely to have forklift / pallet jack traffic. Not only use dunnage in trailers to protect hazardous shipments but also on the dock as well when hazardous shipments are staged.

column168: Driver finished loading the product Black Liquor at the Sappi Fine Paper's loading station located at door #7.  When he completed loading he closed the dome lid and tightened down the dogs on the dome cover.  The driver didn't notice when doing this that the gasket around the dome cover had gotten pinched in the dome cover.  Since the dome cover gasket was pinched it resulted in an improper seal around the dome cover.  The driver drove away unaware there was a problem resulting in a trail of Black Liquor being spilled until the security guard noticed the spillage and immediatley stopped the driver.  The trailer was immediatley brought to a containment area where the spilled product was cleaned off and absorbent socks and wood chips were put in place to absorb the black liquor.  Walker Industrial services was contacted immediatley by Sappi Fine Papers personnel for the clean up.  Tom Griffen from Sappi Fine Papers conducted sampling and testing and reported no damage was done, just the clean up was involved.  Some of the Black Liquor did enter the Sappi Fine sewage drains.  Tom Griffin completed testing on the sedimentation ponds and the results were in normal ranges for discharge from ponds 1, 2, and 3.
column169: Driver will be counseled on proper cargo securement.  A full review will be performed and additional training will be provided to the driver as needed.  The driver must ensure he has a good seal on the dome cover and through additional training and disciplinary actions Superior Carriers will ensure this driver understands the requirements. column168: Compartment 2 of this 4 compartment trailer started leaking ferric chloride while traveling down the interstate.  Other motorists noticed it or got some on their vehicles and got him to pull over (we paid to have the vehicles involved cleaned).  He noticed a steady stream coming from where the valve bolts up to the trailer.  We transferred the product from compartment 2 into compartment 1 and is holding.  DOT released the driver and advised he did a good job.  A response team came out to clean the product off the roadway.  The cause of the leak appeared to be that the valve bolts were loose.
column169: The valves were not loose in this example.  The product is such that it pits stainless steel.  We recognized this would be an issue over the long term so we had a special valve installed on that compartment.  At some point the trailer came in for maintenence and a simple part for that valve was broken.  The mechanic recognized he did not have that piece for this type of valve assembly and that it was not the standard valve that usually is on this type of trailer.  He had removed that valve and installed a factory valve.  Over the course of multiple loads the valve pitted through and started leaking.  As a result both the valve on compartment 2 and compartment 1 are being replaced now that the delivery was complete.  The mechanic was trained on the importance of questioning why specific parts are on a trailer that don't appear to be stock equipment.  He had the right mindset in that trailers should be kept with manufacturer parts but he also needed to understand that there may be instances in which alternate valves may be installed for specific chemicals.

column168: Driver arrived at destination, (customer), was let into the facility and diredted to the unloading point. The plant operator, (same person that let driver into plant), verified paperwork and went to the bank of unloading pipes, signed off on the paperwork that the driver was authorized to unload and left. All unloading stations were locked except one. The driver connected to the unlocked station and proceeded to unload. Upon completion of the unloading he went to the building to get the operator and noticed liquid in a containment inside the building and ask the operator about it. Th operator went into a panic stating he was "sorry it was the wrong valve and he was so fired". The valve left unlocked that the driver hooked to was a sump line from the contianment around the tanks.  The product was not released into the environment but into a containment area inside a building.
column169: Plant signage needs to be changed to show each valve in the unloading areas function better than is now showing. Retraining of plant operators on making sure drivers have hooked up to correct line prior to start of unloading process.  Carrier followed proper procedures to verify they were in the right place and had operator sign off stating so. Carrier will also re-address with drivers the need to double verify the proper connection.

column168: ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT JOB #28645/CON-WAY TRUCKLOAD, INC. INCIDENT #2010010001: THE DRIVER OBSERVED A LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE RELEASE HAD IMPACTED AN AREA OF CONCRETE APPROXIMATELY 12 INCHES IN DIAMETER.  CON-WAY TRUCKLOAD, INC. CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGE AND REQUESTED A RESPONSE TO THE RELEASE.  ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT MOBLIZED PERSONNEL FROM TAS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICESS, L.P. (TAS) TO THE INCIDENT SITE.  THE RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ON SITE AND DOOMED THE PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT TO MAKE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER.  IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED AND PUSHED THE DRUMS FOWARD, UP AGAINT PALLETS (UTILIZED FOS SPACING).  ONE 55-GALLON DRUM OF CYMEL 1158 RESIN LOCATED TOWARDS THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER HAD BEEN CRUSHED AT THE BOTTOM BY ANOTHER DRUM AND THE BOTTOM TORE CAUSING A GAP APPROXIMATELY 2 INCHES IN LENGTH.   APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF THE RESIN PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF OF THE TRAILER FLOOR (48-FOOT TRAILER) WAS IMPACTED.  THE DRUM WILL BE LEFT ON SITE PENDING NOTIFICATION FROM THE SHIPPER AS TO THE DISPOSITION OF THE DRUM.  THE RESPONSE TEAM INSPECTED THE OTHER DRUMS AND FOUND NO OTHER DRUMS LEAKING.  THE RESPONSE TEAM THEN UTILIZED ABSORBENT MATERIALS TO CLEAN  UP THE TRAILER FLOOR AND THE AREA ON THE GROUND.  ALL IMPACTED ABSORBENTS WERE RECOVERED AND PLACED INTO ONE 55-GALLON DRUM.  THE ONE 55-GALLON DRUM OF IMPACTED ABSORBENTS WILL BE TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE TAS FACILITY PENDING DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENTS. THE DRUMS THAT WERE NOT DAMAGED WERE LOADED BACK INTO THE TRAILER AND SECURED WITH LOAD LOCKS.  THE UNIT WAS THEN RELEASED.

column168: A van trailer containing 26 Wrangler flex bins of hazardous waste arrived at Clean Harbors Bristol CT facility enroute to its intended waste disposal facility. The driver noticed that there was a leaking flex bin and the van was put in a containment area at the plant. A response crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the trailer and found that a cubic yard box was leaking. The trailer was unloaded and the leaking flex bin was repacked placing the leaking container in an overpack. The trailer floor was cleaned with a cleaning compound and returned to service for continued transport to intended disposal facility.
column169: During the response it was discovered a paint can that was collected from a household hazardous waste collection event ruptured during transportation and spilled its contents into the interior of the cubic yard container. The material leaked through the liner and fiberboard box onto te floor of the van trailer. In order to prevent a recurrence, the entire cleanpack organization in the North East  recieved re-training regarding the terms and conditions of the DOT Special Permit (DOT-SP-11624)authorizing this packaging methodolgy. Specifically, it was stressed that all containers must be inspected and secured, loaded in such a way to prevent movement within the package and packaged in such a way to insure they remain upright within the outer container including proper sorbent material added to container.

column168: After arrival on an inbound BNSF intermodal train at the intermodal hub, FSTZ 882606 was reported leaking an unknown liquid substance onto the deck of the intermodal flatcar it was loaded upon. FSTZ 882606 was carefully removed (deramped) from this flatcar and sent to the facility's containment area for further inspection by BNSF and contract responders. A BNSF contractor removed the lading inside FSTZ 882606 to ascertain the leak source. Inspection of the lading revealed that two 55 gallon steel drums loaded atop a pallet were dented, with one of these drums having a small cut in the dent area above the bottom rolling hoop. The appearance of this damage indicated that it may have been caused by a fork lift tine during loading. The responders over-packed the damaged drum into a poly over-pack drum properly labeled. Spillage atop the intermodal flatcar and inside the trailer was wiped with absorbent pads and the trailer was left to ventilate overnight. Spent cleaning materials were placed into a container for future appropriate disposal by the response contractor. On 4/12/2010, the contract responders reloaded all lading, including the drum over-pack back into FSTZ 882606, properly blocked and braced for continued ground transportation.

column168: Container, HRZU434294-8/TX2918121, was in transit from Puerto Rico, via rail, to Longbeach for transporting on final ocean leg via the Horizon Consumer, CS258S, to Honolulu. Vessel departed 4/16/10 and arrived in Honolulu 4/21/10. During a random inspection by the USCG a leaking material was discovered, on 4/22/10. All pertinent parties were notified and action was taken to address leaking material. During addressing/removal of leaking material, it was discovered the material was UN1866/Class 3 and it was undeclared. A separate report will be filed on the undeclared issue. Leaking drum was placed in an overpack to contained and allow for it to be properly disposed . The rest of the shipment was transferred to another container to continue its movement and allow for the original container to be cleaned. Paperwork was corrected.    MULTIPLE REPORT  (Note: This in conjunction with spill report E-2010050042)  Container, HRZU434294-8/TX2918121, was in transit from Puerto Rico, via rail, Longbeach for transporting on final ocean leg via the Horizon Consumer, CS258S to Honolulu. Vessel departed 4/16/10 and arrived in Honolulu 4/21/10. During random inspection by USCG a leaking material was discovered. (Leak report covered by report noted above).  It was also noted shipper failed to declare UN1866/Class 3, along with UN3091/Class 9, UN3072/Class 9, UN1824/Class 8, and UN3105/Class 5.2 (which was recognized as incompatible Class 8 and Class 3. All parties were notified UN3105/Class 5.2 was removed. The paperwork was updated accordingly, so the rest of shipment could continued. Shipper made arrangements to pick-up UN3105 by itself with paperwork.

MULTIPLE REPORT  Shipper must observe entire loading to capture all hazmat commodities to have accurate paperwork prior to tendering to trucker and ocean carrier. They must also compare hazmat commodities to ensure proper compatibility occurs, and meet regulations.

column168: On April 24, 2010 at 11:30 hrs., personnel in the CSX Transportation Stanley yard in Walbridge, OH, discovered SHPX 207018, a loaded tank car of Ferrous Chloride Solution, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper representative, LLoyd Moore (Cell phone # 416-436-2067), was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2010-04-24-000540).  A CSXT emergency response contractor, SWS/Eagle, was dispatched to the scene to make repairs.  Upon arrival, SWS/Eagle personnel reported the pressure relief vent disc retainer and its plug were not in place but rather dangling at the side of the pressure relief vent nozzle. The pressure relief vent rupture disc was missing. SWS/Eagle reported less than 5 gallons of material was atop the tank with none on the ground. SWS/Eagle personnel assembled the pressure relief vent assembly and the leak stopped.  The car was decontaminated and released for further transport.  Cause Code: 437  NARRI: 5 (5+5+0) X (2+0) = 100

A van trailer containing multiple containers of hazardous waste was unloaded at the intermediate transfer facility for reloading onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  When unloading, it was noticed that a pallet was puched against a drum, which was dented.  The drum was not leaking on the trailer, but when unloaded and sitting on the dock, it was noticed to be slowly leaking out of a pinhole leak where the dent had cracked the body.  The dock worker donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the drum into a suitable salvage container.  The spilled material was cleaned up with an absorbent material which was also placed into the salvage drum.  The drum was then loaded onto the proper trailer and proceeded without further incident to the destination.  LA State Police were notified, incident report number 10-02264

column168: FRA inspectors in the railyard reported UTLX 46929 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with product spillage on its side shell to the local BNSF terminal trainmaster. After visual inspection, UTLX 46929 was carefully moved to an isolated repair track in the railyard for a detailed inspection by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder. The BNSF responder reported that one of the two PRD's (pressure relief device) affixed atop this tank car was the leak source. The leaking 75 psi PRD was inspected and found to have the bottom stem nuts missing which nullified valve spring operation and prevented this PRD from functioning normally; thus allowing minimal amounts of product to escape during rail movement. Non-evaporated spillage on the shell of UTLX 46929 was wiped. A replacement PRD was ordered by a shipper affiliate to be installed by UTC (Union Tank Car). On 4/29/2010, a UTC technician installed the replacement PRD and followed this installation with a tank car leak test of the PRD. The bubble leak test was completed and deemed acceptable. Response was concluded by 1000 hrs. PDT, 4/29/2010. UTLX 46929 was forwarded to the consignee for unloading afterwards.

column168: ON APRIL 12, 2010 A NH 3 NURSE TANK LEFT THE CAMDEN FACILITY (RURAL HUNTSVILLE ADRESS).  THE NURSE TANK NUMBER WAS C5.  THE DESTINATION WAS MUSICK FARMS NEAR AUGUSTA, ILLINOIS.  THE DRIVER HEADED WEST ON THE LAPRAIRIE BLACKTOP.  THE WAGON STARTED TO WHIP BACK AND FORTH SIDEWAYS.  THE DRIVER TRIED TO SLOW DOWN TO ELIMINATE THE WHIP.  THE WAGON WHIPPED HARDER AS HE TRIED TO SLOW.  THE TANK BOUNCED AND THEN ROLLED OVER.  WHEN IT ROLLED OVER, IT SNAPPED THE END OF THE TONGUE ON THE WAGON ON THE WELD JOINT.  THE TANK CAGE BROKE WHEN THE WAGON ROLLED OVER SNAPPING THE LIQUID WITHDRAWAL VALVE.  ANHYDROUS WAS DISPERSED INTO THE AIR.  THE DRIVER THEN CALLED HIS PLANT MANAGER WHO SAW THAT THE APPROPRIATE AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.  THE LOCAL LEPC WAS ON SITE AS WELL AS A SHERIFF DEPUTY.  A STRONG WIND BLEW FROM THE SOUTH ALLOWING TRAFFIC TO BE DIRECTED BY ONE LANE AT A TIME.  AFTER THE MATERIAL HAD RELEASED OUR COMPANY REMOVED THE WAGON FROM THE ROAD.
column169: TWO RIVERS FS TRAINS ALL OF OUR DRIVERS TO SAFELY TRANSPORT ALL MATERIALS.  THE DRIVER IN THIS INCIDENT HAD EIGHT YEARS EXPERIENCE.

column168: Road driver was here to take TL 84906 to 064 Dayton.  Road driver said TL had a strange chemical spill and wanted to call safety. I then walked out to TL and my dock man to instruct him to back the TL in and we will take off freight and see if we can find leaking tote.   When I walked out, I noticed residue on TL floor at rear, just few ounces and the chemical smell.  Did notice it had dripped down on rear of trailer but nothing dripping/leaking at current time. Letting TL air out so smell will go away and can ship out later.  No other totes leaking.

column168: On 04/12/2010, Rohm and Haas Electronics Materials LLC, a wholly-owned subsidiary of The Dow Chemical Company, located on 60 Willow St., North Andover, MA 01845, received an undeclared package containing hazardous materials.  The package shipped from ReagentWorld, located at 2048 East Francis St., Ontario, CA 91761.  The outer package was a United States Postal Service medium flat-rate box with no hazardous material labels or documentation.  The inner packaging was a Federal Express bubble pack containing 2 separate plastic bags of hazardous materials.  One bag contained 3 kg of Nickel Chloride, which is a Class 6.1, PG III hazardous material.  The other bag contained 2 kg of Lantham Metal, which is a class 4.3, PG I hazardous material.  There was no release or exposure.  MSDS for each material was not provided with package but was requested and received from the shipper that confirmed both materials are hazardous materials.  Note that there will be a Hazardous Materials Incident Report completed for each hazardous material in the package.    SUPPLEMENTAL ADDED THIS STATEMENT:    AS FOLLOW-UP, PACKAGE MAY HAVE SHIPPED FROM DANNIER CHEMICAL INC LOCATED AT 2192 DUPONT DRIVE, SUITE 214, IRVINE, CA 92612.
column169: A root cause investigation was immediately requested from the shipper and is currently in progress.

column168: Inbound inspection of a BNSF intermodal train in the railyard revealed entrained loaded intermodal flatcar (CSXT 620016) with wheel truck side bearing defects. This flatcar was setout of the train. Later, during off loading (deramping) of intermodal containers loaded atop this flatcar, container CMAU 513601 was observed dripping an unknown liquid substance from several locations at the bottom of this container. CMAU 513601 was carefully removed and isolated in the intermodal parking area awaiting a detailed inspection. (CMAU 513601 was an export shipment destined Australia and scheduled to depart from the port of Long Beach, CA). The shipper arranged for a response contractor to inspect CMAU 513601. The responders reported finding two steel drums towards the middle of this 40 foot container partially crushed by a heavy diesel engine placed atop the drums with the only separation being a single sheet 1/2 inch particleboard. This heavy weight caused the drums to buckle and the drum's upper sidewall to crack releasing some contents. Only one of these drums was identified as containing hazardous material. The compromised drums were overpacked. Responders neutralized and cleaned the spillage inside the container, on the ground and atop the intermodal flatcar. On 4/14/2010, the responders reloaded the container properly blocked and braced for further rail transport to the destination port. The overpacked drums and some other lading that would not properly fit inside the container after the lading was reconfigured were earmarked to be returned to the origin shipper. CMAU 513601's billing was adjusted to reflect manifest change.
column169: Ensure shipper properly blocks and braces lading inside intermodal shipping containers; and weight limitations are employed when stacked lading is utilized within the loading pattern.

column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: OUR TRUCK WAS OUT FOR DELIVERY WITH TWO 330 GL CAPACITY TOTES FILLED WITH 300 GL OF BLEACH EACH.  THESE TOTES WERE POSITIONED IN THE CENTER OF THE 27FT. STAKE BED TRAILER.  IN FRONT OF THE TWO TOTES WAS A 1050 GL CAPACITY PORTABLE TANK FILLED TO 1000 GL POSITIONED WITH THE DISCHARGE VALVE FACING TOWARD THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE 1050 GL TANK WAS SECURED WITH TWO 2" NYLON RATCHET STRAPS (3335 LBS WEIGHT RATING) POSITIONED IN FRONT AND IN BACK OF THE TOTES, LATCHED TO THE SIDE RACKS, A DISTANCE HALFWAY FROM THE BOTTOM TO THE TOP OF THE TOTES.  AS OUR DRIVER TRAVELED NORTH, THERE WAS 2 TO 3 VEHICLES IN FRONT OF HIM A, ALL DRIVING 45 MPH AND AT ABOUT 400 TO 500 YARDS SOUTH OF RANCHO VISTOS BLVD., AND UNIDENTIFIED VEHICLE ABRUPTLY BREAK.  TO AVOID A COLLISION WITH THE VEHICLES, OUR DRIVER PUMPED HIS BREAKS AT A RATE THAT CAUSED THE TWO TOTES TO SHIFT FORWARD BREAKING THE 2" NYLON RATCHET STRAP AND STRIKING THE DISCHARGE VALVE OFF OF THE 100 GL SKID TANK AND BREAKING IT OFF COMPLETELY.  OUR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTICED BLEACH RUNNING OFF THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND IMMEDIATELY PULLED OFF THE ROAD ONTO THE SHOULDER TO LOOK AT THE SITUATION AND PROMPTLY CALLED HIS OFFICE TO REPORT.  THE BRANCH MANAGER CALLED GOLDEN RANCH FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HILL BROTHERS COMPLIANCE DEPARTMENT.  IT TOOK APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES FOR THE 920 GALLONS TO LEAK OUT.  THE GOLDEN RANCH FIRE DEPARTMENT MIXED WATER WITH THE SOLUTION AND IT SPREAD 350-400 FEET.  AS OF MAY 5TH THE FILE WITH SOUTHWEST HAZARD CONTROL AND AZCOT HAS BEEN CLOSED DUE TO THE PH LEVELS TESTING BETWEEN 8 AND 9.
column169: DISCONTINUED USE OF 1050 GL TANK UNTIL VALVE POSITION HAS BEEN ADDRESSED AND CORRECTED.  TRAINING ON LOAD SECUREMENT HAS BEEN CONDUCTED.

column169: PLACE DUNNAGE UNDER DRUMS, BAGS, PAILS AND TOTES TO PREVENT SHARP OR POINTED OBJECTS FROM PUNCTURING THE BOTTOM. column17: United Transport of East Longmeadow, Inc.
column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling on Route 9 East, driver was involved in a vehicle accident, which caused the cargo tank truck to rollover.  Two (2) tanks were connected to the truck, one (1) which contained approximately 7,999 gallons of fuel oil, and one (1) which contained approximately 2,000 gallons of diesel fuel.  The entire contents of the tank(s) were released to the roadway, entered into the nearby storm drains, and ran down into a culvert.  The Highway Department responded with sand trucks to attempt to contain the free product.  Western Mass Environmental of West Springfield, Massachusetts was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Western Mass Environmental assisted the local authorities, and responding agencies in recovering the free product.  Approximately 8,000 gallons of free product were recovered with the use of their vacuum truck.  The storm drainage system was flushed to recover all residual products and prevent migration to the nearby River.  A Licensed Site Professional (LSP) was hired to oversee cleanup activity, and prepare necessary report documentation, as required by MADEP.  Crews worked on site for several days to cleanup all affected areas and restore site to preexisting condition.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a vehicle accident, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  United Transport of East Longmeadow, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

At approxomately 10:00 the Linde driver was travelling West on I26 near Saluda, NC. He was climbing Saluda Mountain at 35-40 mph and was in the middle lane. He was passing a Pope Transport gasoline tractor trailer. A red Jeep was in the 3rd lane (fast lane) beginning to pass the Linde driver. A Dodge pick up truck coming up behind the Linde truck switched lanes to the 3rd lane and impacted the Jeep. The driver of the Jeep lost control and hit the vaporizer on the Linde trailer. The Jeep then hit the Pope Transport truck on its driver side.    The driver of the Jeep was taken to a local hospital with minor injuries (pain in her ankle). There was no other passenger in the Jeep.    The vaporizer was secured to the trailer by the Midland, NC Linde mechanic and the Linde driver brought it back to Midland and placed it out of service.    The driver of the Dodge truck was cited for an improper lane change.    Our driver maintained control of his vehicle and safely stopped in the emergency lane to the right.    The DOT inspection of the Linde vehicle noted no deficiencies other than the damage the Jeep had caused. Once the vaporizer and hose tube were secured the Linde vehicle was released to return to the Midland depot.
column169: Linde vehicle and driver were not at fault.  Damage caused was minimal.  No recommended corrective actions at this time.

column168: As unit approached intersection of Hwy 64 and Blue Pkwy in Asheboro, NC, the product inside the tank surged forward, the front clean-out cap blew off spewing product from the clean-out nipple.  The cap apparently had not been properly tightened prior to loading.  Approximately 20 gallons of product was spilled onto the tractor and roadway.  Police, Fire and EMS responded, Fire stood by until spill was cleaned up by an independent spill clean up company A & D Environmental from High Point, NC.  Oil dry was used to clean up the spilled product, which was transported and disposed of by A & D. The cap was replaced and secured on the unit and unit was released to proceed to destination without further mishap.      Later that night a passerby called to report she had to go to the hospital due to inhaling the fumes from the product which had been spilled, no report of the injury at the time of the incident.

column168: Intermodal tank container NRSU 192012 (IM 101) was reported with a liquid substance dripping from the tank bottom while it was being staged to be loaded atop an intermodal rail flatcar. NRSU 192012 was carefully moved and placed inside the BNSF's intermodal facility's containment area (pit) for further investigation. A BNSF response contractor inspected NRSU 192012 and tested the dripping substance for acidity. The liquid drips were confirmed to be the sulfuric acid. Ground impact areas observed were neutralized. The reported leak source was at the bottom front tank at the exterior support frame weld area. Shipper agents were notified and procured a suitable replacement tank container for transference of product from NRSU 192012. The product transfer was completed on 4/22/2010 without further incident and with no additional product leakage from NRSU 192012 once emptied. The spilled material inside the containment pit was diluted by standing water already in the pit and then neutralized by the contract responder. All liquid in the pit was vacuumed, cleaning the containment pit.

column14: I-20/595 off ramp to I-359 N
column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While on exit ramp to Highway 359, the tractor-tanker unit rolled over.  The roll-over was apparently the result of exiting the ramp too fast.  As a result the load shifted and the tanker rolled over near the center median of the highway.  This action caused a large fire, which resulted in the death of the driver.  The tractor-tanker unit was carrying approximately 5595 gallons of gasoline and 1994 gallons of diesel fuel.  The Alabama State Police, Tuscaloosa Fire Department, Alabama Department of Transportation and the Tuscaloosa Emergency Management Agency responded to assess the site.  The Tuscaloosa Fire Department extinguished the fire.  The fire caused significant damage to an area approximately 1500 feet long and 12 feet wide on the highway.  The degraded asphalt was milled and transported by the Alabama Department of Transportation contractor for recycling.  The highway was reopened at approximately 1:15am EST on April 10, 2010.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and may have been the result of exiting the ramp too fast, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, M & S Cartage will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Newsom Trucking Inc. delivered a load of Sodium Hypochlorite to Vertex’s consignee, Prairie State Generating, LLC in Marissa, IL.  The driver arrived at the consignee site and was told by the consignee that the entire load would fit into the designated storage tank.  The driver proceeded to unload the product into the specified tank at the consignee site.  There was not sufficient room in the tank to hold the entire load and the tank overflowed approximately 100 gallons at the end of the transfer.  The driver was able to shut off the transfer and save an additional 250 gallons from releasing.  It was later discovered that the consignee tank digital level gauge was not properly working.  The storage tank is opaque and the level can not be viewed by drivers or operators.  No backup high level alarm was installed in the tank.  The spilled product was contained in a containment pit and was properly neutralized and disposed of.
column169: A review of the incident was conducted with drivers of Newsom Trucking, Inc, Vertex and the consignee.  Clean up was conducted by the consignee.

column168: At approximately 11:1 5AM on 4-26-2010 a clear 60 degree and sunny day, Dan Schwartz our propane bobtail deliveryman was traveling south on Wisconsin State Highway 35 at the junction of Big McGraw Road about 13 miles north of Danbury, WI. He was going to turn left (east). Dan just started to slow down to make his turn when he noticed a blue Ford Ranger pickup crossing the centerline coming towards him. Dan pulled over to the right as far as he could go without going into the ditch. He saw the older male pickup drivers eyes wide open kind of in a daze staring forward. The pickup hit our truck in the front drivers wheel, then it hit our back fender and two backsets of wheels. The pickup then rolled over ending up in the southbound lane on its roof and topper. The unidentified pickup driver died at the scene, Dan had no injuries. Dan called 911 and his supervisor Bill Wasko right alter it happened. Police preliminary speculation looks like it may have been a medical situation that caused the pickup driver to loose control of his vehicle. The Wisconsin State Patrol was at the scene and did all of the post-accident investigation work including Dan’s report of what happened and a complete bobtail inspection, which came out real good. Prescription drugs were found by the totally devastated pickup. Emergency personnel were at the scene for traffic control and the extensive parts cleanup. I called the Wisconsin Duty Officer even though there was no release, that case number is #McDonoughO426lO and I will follow up with the required DOT reports. There was no release of propane. The bobtail had 30% in it at the time of the accident and was pumped out into another bobtail brought onto the scene by Dan Saumer from our Sandstone plant. Then Ostrom’s Towing of Minong, WI, towed it to our Danbury plant. It seems the truck may be drivable to the repair shops when we replace the three wheels. Apparently there was a witness, a Schwan’s deliveryman who the State Patrol has or will be contacting. Dan did a very good job of controlling his truck and not rolling it in the ditch. All of his paperwork seemed to be in order. I will be getting a police report as soon as it comes available. Federated contacts for those at the scene are: Bill Wasko Danbury and Gordon Plants Manager 715-376-2264, mobile 715-558-6355, Mark Grave, Propane Division Manager mobile 218-522-1440, and myself Tom Rausch, Safety Director, mobile 763-286-2299. Mike Chmielecki an employee from our Gordon plant was also there helping out and can be reached through Bill Wasko. If there are any questions please call me at 763-286- 2299 and I’ll get whatever we need.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Vacuum Relief Valve
column62: Defective Component or Device; Threads Worn or Cross Threaded
column168: A FRA Safety Inspector's inspection of railcars in the railyard, revealed DBUX 300221 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with product wetness at the bottom outlet closure cap (BOC). The BOC appeared tool tight and this bottom operated bottom outlet valve (BOV) was in the closed position with its operating handle pinned. During further inspection of DBUX 300221, the FRA Inspector also found the threaded vacuum relief valve (VRV) emanating vapor forming bubbles at its threaded connection which also displayed wetness. A BNSF mechanical foreman accompanying the FRA inspector coordinated careful movement of DBUX 300221 to an isolated area in the railyard and arranged for a response contractor to fully inspect DBUX 300221. Inspection of DBUX 300221 by the BNSF contractor concurred with the aforementioned observations. The contractor vented DBUX 300221 to reduce internal pressure within the tank. This immediately eliminated vapor escaping at the base of the VRV. Visual inspection inside the tank car via the open manway surmised one gallon or less of liquid remained at the bottom of the tank. With a receptacle under the BOV, the BOC was removed to check the BOC gasket and the internal ball valve condition. The BOC had product residue inside the cap and the BOC gasket, although aged, appeared serviceable. The BOV was cycled open/closed releasing approx. 1/2 gallon of product into the receptacle. The internal ball valve appeared to allow product to by-pass this valve when in the closed position. The BOV + BOC were cleaned and resecured. Afterwards, no further product wetness was observed at the BOC.  The consignee (Tesoro Refining + Marketing Co.) requested a FRA movement approval to move DBUX 300221 to a qualified repair facility and FRA-10050295 was granted 05/19/2010.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On April 15, 2010, Veolia employees discovered a leaking 5-gallon jerrican while unloading a truck at the Veolia, Latham transfer facility. Approximately one gallon of material leaked onto the floor of the commercial motor vehicle. It was determined that the container leaked due to shifting while in transportation.  The cap of the jerrican was a loose causing a slow leak to develop. The container was transferred to another vehicle, secured upright, and the cap of the container was tightly sealed. The remainder of the material was shipped to a properly permitted TSDF for treatment. The material on the floor of the truck was remediated with speedi dri and also sent to a TSDF for proper treatment. The container information is as follows: 3H1/Y1.8/100/10/USA/M-2030. The container was purchased from Tricorbraun.
column169: A meeting was set up with the Veolia Supervisor responsible for the shipment and the incident was investigated. The incident was discussed and package closure instructions will be followed more thoroughly in the future.  The incident was also reviewed in a training session with all Veolia, New England hazmat employees.

column14: RAMP FROM I 255 AT MILE POST 1
column168: Tractor and trailer was exiting 1-255 in a light rain. Driver said he was traveling at approximately 20 mph into a right curve when the left steer tire dropped off the paved part of the shoulder into the gravel and started to slide. The driver said he hit the brake and turned the steering wheel to the right. The product on the trailer sloshed to the left side of the tank and pushed the tractor and trailer onto it's left side, then rolled over and came to rest on it's right side. The driver climbed out of the truck and contacted his supervisor, then called the State Police. The supervisor contacted a hazardous materials response contractor who determined that no release had occurred. The trailer was pumped off onto another tanker and removed from the scene. Upon inspection of the tanker it was discovered that welds on the interior left wall had cracked and the baffles collapsed. A bulkhead between compartment one and two pushed through the outer skin on the left side of the tank, but because it rolled onto it's right side no product was lost.Because of the internal damage and the torn outer shell along with the age of the tank it is considered a total loss.
column169: Retrain drivers concerning speed going into a turn. Slowing down well before a curve will reduce the risk of a rollover.

column168: Unit 1 towing Unit 2 was travelling southwest on US 62 and failed to negotiate a curve. Advisory speed was 50 MPH. Unit 1 and Unit 2 struck guard rail. two lights.then rolled and separated. Unit 1 came to rest on left side and Unit 2 came to rest on it's right side at the next guard rail, (as reported by TX Department of Public Safety/TX Highway Patrol) First Responders notified P.E.R.S who, in turn, notified Propane Direct Enterprises at approximately 12:30 hrs. Adam Breakell of Propane Direct Enterprises notified the TX Railroad Comission at approximately 12:50 hrs and then notified TX Commission of Environmental Quality at 12:56 hrs. The National Response Center was notified at 17:50 hrs and a follow-up report to the TXCEQ was made at 17:52 hrs.The Driver was brought to University Medical Center in El Paso.TX via local ambulance. At approximately 14:00 hrs the TX Department of Public Safety was able to confirm that there was NOT any releaseof hazardous materials. Propane Direct Enterprises dispatched three employees and two trucks to the scene at approximately 14:00 hrs to pump out product from the over-turned vessel into another vessel to be delivered to the original destination in Clint.TX. All product transfer was completed by approximately 20:30 hrs and the scene was totally cleared of all equipment by approximately 22:00 hrs. (ALL TIMES ARE Central Time)
column169: Our company is doing a review of it's driver training process and will be implementing additional driver safety tips and policies along with our regular safety meetings. We plan to use this incident as an example of how safety should bethe first policy at Propane Direct Enterprises.

DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING TOTES CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING.  LIDS AND OTHER CLOSURES MUST BE TIGHT TO PREVENT LIDS FROM LOOSENING, RELEASING THE LIQUID.  THE DURABILITY OF THE DRUM, PAIL BAGS AND/OR TOTE MUST BE ABLE TO MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION.  IMPORTATNT THAT LISDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE.  TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFETY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER, PACKAGING MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID AND POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED.  DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  PACKAGINGS OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN!

MAINTENANCE MUST BE DONE PROPERLY TO ENSURE SAFE USE FOR ALL.  WHEN ENTERING OR EXITING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS, OR TOTES LOADED OR STACKED ON THE FLOOR; ON A PLATFORM AND/OR HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS.  FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT.  DISCUSS, DURING PRESHIFT, ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUID OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS!  PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGE AND PUNCTURING.  LEAVE PAIL OF HAZARDOUS OR CHEMICAL IN THE BAY UNTIL TRAILER IS READY FOR CLOSE.  EMPLOYEE GIVEN COACHING ON LOADING AND DOCK AWARENESS.

column168: In response to the discovery of the incident, an immediate notification to the National Response Center was made by telephone in accordance with 49 CFR 171.15.  Our transportation manager notified the duty officer, Petty Officer Huggins.  PO Huggins assigned case number 938679 to the incident report.  The telephonic report was made conservatively prior to the time at which the investigation could be completed.  After our investigation, the evidence leads us to believe that the leak of contents did not occur during transport but was limited to our facility.  Furthermore, the leak appears to have happened subsequent to the carrier relinquishing custody of the shipment to EnergySolutions.  Because of these facts, the incident was not an immediately reportable incident in accordance with 49 CFR 171.15, and a detailed report is therefore not required.  The following information is provided as clarification and background: On the  morning of April 30, 2010, personnel at the EnergySolutions Bear Creek Road Facility in Oak Ridge, TN discovered an oily residue on a transport vehicle (shipment manifest number 09-5-029) near the doors of a large freight container (container number 9260009) while removing the freight containers from the transport vehicle.  Upon further investigation, the oily residue was found on several areas of the trailer and the ground at our facility where the vehicle was a parked and the freight.  Because the freight container contained Class 7 material, a radiological survey was performed.  The areas on the transport vehicle and ground where the oily residue could be seen had detectable levels of contamination.  The shipment consisting of two large freight containers holding waste material from SERF-5 left the AREVA facility on 04/28/2010 at 10:30 a.m. for EnergySolutions located in Oak Ridge, Tennessee.  The shipment arrived at the EnergySolutions facility on the afternoon of April 28, 2010 at 4:22 PM (after normal working hours).  The shipment was inspected and surveyed for radioactive material on the morning of April 29, 2010.  The radiological survey did not indicate the presence of contamination.  Radiological surveys of the transport vehicle indicated a maximum removable contamination level of about 17,000 dpm/100 cm2 of beta-gamma activity.  Assuming 10% removal efficiency, there was approximately 170,000 dpm/100 cm2 of beta-gamma total activity of the package.  The limit in this case is 220,000 dpm/100 cm2 of beta-gamma total activity on the package.EnergySolutions'' Health Physics personnel isolated the area around transport vehicle and freight containers involved in this shipment.The rear-most container (container number 9260009) was found to be leaking the oily substance from the doors.  EnergySolutions personnel constructed a cover to prevent further spread of contamination.  The container and transport vehicle were moved to a building where the radioactive contamination could be managed appropriately.The frieght container

column168: Driver was delivering a load of Diesel(6999 Gallons)to the tank farm in Rifle Colorado. On Loveland Pass,approaching a sharp hairpin curve and going to fast for the curve, rolled the tractor trailer truck over onto the right side of the roadway. Rolling over a guard rail and crushing the guard rail. The MC406 trailer received several punctures and the fuel was leaking from the caps. The tractor trailer came to a rest on it's top. Belfor Enviromental company was called and they we on scene in forty minites. Belfor had a crew appling fuel soaking booms below the spill area to contain the spill. Gilco had another truck sent to the accident site to retrieve (Pump Out) the remaining fuel. Gilco pumped out 4879 gallons of fuel from the trailer as so the tow truck can remove the tractor trailer truck. Belfor Enviromental is still monitoring the spill site to this day.
column169: Further Training. Simple close Loveland pass for Hazmat vehicles, allow them to drive through the eisenhower tunnels. Loveland Pass is a very narrow with no guard rails in areas and very sharp curves and step grades. Very dangerous in the Winter months. There has been hundreds of tanker accidents on Loveland pass every year.

column168: 300-gallon tote of sulfuric acid was being unloaded from a truck by forklift.  The tote shifted on the forklift, causing it to fall to the ground.  The tote ruptured, spilling the sulfuric acid on to the ground.  The spill was contained on the asphalt of the parking lot and did not enter any drain or waterway.  the Holston Army Ammunition Plant onsite fire department responded to the spill initially and put down soda ash to ensure spill containment.  A remediation contractor was then called to come and clean up material.  The material was neutralized with mag oxide, collected, pH tested and upon determination of neutral pH was taken to the installation's onsite lined Class II landfill in accordance with the agreement of Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation RCRA personnel.
column169: The use of totes was a temproary process until a large sulfuric acid tank could be repaired.  The regular sulfuric acid tank is back in service and the use of totes has been discontinued.

column168: ON 4/21/10, APPROXIMATELY 5:50 AM, WHILE TRAVELING EAST ON NC 47 IN DAVIDSON COUNTY NEAR DENTON, NORTH CAROLINA, THE DRIVER ENCOUNTERED A SUDDENT AND SEVERE RAIN STORM WHILE STILL DARK.  THE DRIVER, SLOWING HIS SPEED DOWN TO APPROXIMATELY 35 MPH, CAME INTO A DOWNHILL CURVE WHICH CURVED TO THE RIGHT.  AT THIS POINT THE DRIVER LOST SIGHT OF THE LINES ON THE ROAD.  HE WAS ALREADY EXPERIENCING THE PRODUCT SURGING IN THE TANK. AS HE WAS STEERINGTO THE RIGHT TRYING TO MAINTAIN CONTROL, THE SURGE ROLLED THE VEHICLE OVER ON THE LEFT SIDE, SLIDING OFF THE LEFT SIDE OF THE ROAD STRIKING A LARGE TREE WITH THE CARGO TANK NEAR THE REAR BREACHING THE TANK AND TEARING THE TANK INTO TWO (2) PIECES.  THE TOTAL CONTENTS OF THE CARGO TANK (ASPHALT) SPILLED ON THE GROUND AND RAN INTO A SMALL STREAM.  AS SOON AS THE ASPHALT MADE CONTACT WITH THE WATER IT COOLED AND BECAME A SOLID.  THE DRIVER FREED HIMSELF FROM THE TRUCK AND RECEIVED ASSISTANCE FROM A MOTORIST IN CALLING 911 TO REPORT THE ACCIDENT.  THE TOWN OF DENTON FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AS WELL AS DAVIDSON COUNTY EMS AND NC HIGHWAY PATROL.  THE DENTON FIRE DEPARTMENT ASSISTED THE DRIVER IN CONTACTING OUR OPERATIONS MANAGER WHO IN TURN CONTACTED ME TO REPORT THE ACCIDENT.  DAVIDSON COUNTY EMS TRANSPORTED THE DRIVER TO THOMASVILLE MEDICAL CENTER WHERE HE WAS TREATED FOR MINOR CUTS AND SCRAPES THEN RELEASED.  AT THE TIME I RECEIVED REPORT OF THE ACCIDENT (APPROXIMATELY 6:00 AM); I CALLED BATTLEGROUND TIRE & WRECKER TO RECOVER THE VEHICLE.  I THEN CALLED ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS & SERVICES TO MANAGE THE CLEANUP OF THE PRODUCT.
column169: ACCIDENT COUNTER MEASURES HAVE BEEN TAKEN AND INCLUDE REMEDIAL TRAINING OF ALL OF OUR CARGO TANK DRIVERS IN DRIVING TECHNIQUES AND RE-ROUTED OPERATIONS AWAY FROM THIS RURAL ROAD AND TO USE ONLY MAJOR TRUCK ROUTES WHERE POSSIBLE.
